attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, Intel 80386, version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, stripped

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This ELF binary is a sophisticated Linux malware, likely a variant of a Remote Access Trojan (RAT) or a proxy-based botnet agent. Key indicators of malicious intent include heavy string and data obfuscation via an XOR-based decryption routine (sub_8060f00) used throughout the code. The sample exhibits classic persistence behaviors such as daemonization (sub_80af045) using setsid, chdir("/"), and I/O redirection to /dev/null. It features modular capabilities for network manipulation, specifically SOCKS proxy management (cmy_socks_mgr) and port forwarding (cport_fwd_mgr). Secure communication is supported through embedded RSA public/private key handling. Furthermore, it implements process cloning and command execution via /bin/sh (sub_804f660), providing remote shell access. Relevant IOCs include the decryption function at 0x8060f00, the use of Google DNS (8.8.8.8) for connectivity checks, and obfuscated strings such as 'mrrq3sim3roz'.
